text:
As time goes on I'm more and more convinced that it takes a certain kind of person to do DevRel work. Apart from skillsets such as communication, writing, or marketing, to be a good DevReal you actually have to give a damn about your users and their experience with the product. It's way too easy as an engineer to dismiss someone's complaint because you think you're right. Most engineers aren't even using the final product on a regular basis and forget the context people exist in. @kyletut from the first day said that since I talk to the people, I have to keep the company from falling into fiction, a narrative that says "no we're ok the users are wrong." That's the complacency that will kill your company. 

TLDR: I SPEAK FOR THE DEVELOPERS

text:
It’s close but not quite there afaik. In regard to SRI it can be used to verify some of the downloaded code, however “this has limited utility for CIDs since the SHA256 hash matches the hash in the CID only if the resources were encoded with raw leaves and fit into a single IPFS Block; because IPFS chunks files before hashing and may result in different hashes” source: https://blog.ipfs.tech/dapps-ipfs/

That same article also points to that fact that DNSLink isn’t verifiable so it can be subject to the same security concerns. 

I think those are all things you could add to help boost ever so slightly the security of a site on IPFS but there isn’t a silver bullet for non-ipfs node retrieval.

I think my main point is any approach outside of IPFS node retrieval is gonna have a fault a one point or another. I personally think our approach at Orbiter is balanced and takes good steps to provide sufficient security with the ability to verify with p2p IPFS.

text: TLDR: true client side verification on IPFS still requires an IPFS node, but there is work being done to make that not the case or at the very least make it simpler for consumers

bio.text: DX Engineer | Head of Developer Relations at /pinata | Building orbiter.host | stevedylan.dev/links

text:
IPFS shipyard actually has something similar that’s essentially a gateway in a service worker. The only downside is that it’s also not a perfect system, as service workers have to download code that could be compromised. The only way to truly achieve client side verification is with a local IPFS node and visiting the CID directly. https://x.com/IPFS/status/1899029601487073420 

Good write up on this by Daniel the DevRel at IPFS shipyard, and he even mentioned IPCM as a solution https://blog.ipfs.tech/2025-could-ipfs-prevent-bybit-hack/

As with many other Web3 systems I think it falls into the trust yet verify category; you can trust Orbiter is serving the correct content with the speed and convenience of a traditional domain, but you can also verify it for yourself through IPFS and smart contracts directly.

We are planning to integrate a wallet sign in the near future, so good point there 

We don’t do DNSLink or browser side verification, mostly because we don’t think it’s really necessary for the following reasons: 

- Every site has an IPCM.dev contract where you can trace the version history of each site 
- You can query the contract directly to get the latest CID and visit it on a p2p level with an IPFS node 
- We expose the CID and the contract address in the headers for every website request: https://warpcast.com/polluterofminds/0x8ed7e33a

Last point I might add is that we are open sourced 🫡

text:
Still not totally convinced of that personally. AI generated code will slowly start putting out more and more bad code, models with train on it, spit out even worse code, etc. It’s a reality we’re already starting to see on GitHub, and we’ll probably get to a point where the code AI gives you will only work to an extent or just be busted from the beginning. Not to mention how fast development frameworks move, as AI could give you conflicting libraries or struggle to keep up with the changes being made.  

I do agree that we’re perhaps approaching “end user programming” which is dope and something I want to see, but it will be for smaller problems and projects. Great read on that here: https://www.inkandswitch.com/end-user-programming/
